VI. COMPARATIVE CLAUSES.

399. comparative clauses are either introduced by relative adjectives and adverbs, or by comparative conjunctions. Comparative clauses fre- quently appear in an abbreviated form, so that their predicate, and sometimes other terms of the clause, must be supplied from the princi- pal sentence (see the examples to R. 219 and {g 403. 405).
